# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lloyd-mcclendon
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1980-major-league-baseball-draft] The **1980 Major League Baseball draft** took place in June 1980.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1980-major-league-baseball-draft] The draft saw the New York Mets select Darryl Strawberry first overall.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1980-major-league-baseball-draft] The following are the first round picks in the 1980 Major League Baseball draft.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1987-major-league-baseball-season] The **1987 Major League Baseball season** ended with the American League Champion Minnesota Twins winning the World Series over the National League Champion St.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1987-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, four games to three, as all seven games were won by the home team.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1987-major-league-baseball-season] In June, future Hall of Fame outfielder Ken Griffey Jr. was selected with the number one overall pick in the Major League Baseball draft, by the Seattle Mariners.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1988-major-league-baseball-season] The **1988 Major League Baseball season** ended with the underdog Los Angeles Dodgers shocking the Oakland Athletics, who had won 104 games during the regular season, in the World Series.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1988-major-league-baseball-season] The most memorable moment of the series came in Game 1, when injured Dodger Kirk Gibson hit a dramatic pinch-hit walk-off home run off Athletics closer Dennis Eckersley to win the game for Los Angeles.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1988-major-league-baseball-season] The Dodgers went on to win the Series in five games.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1988-major-league-baseball-season] This would also be the final full season for Peter Ueberroth as MLB commissioner.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1988-major-league-baseball-season] One of the American League's best players in 1988 was Athletics outfielder José Canseco, who became the first player in history to hit 40 home runs and steal 40 bases in a single season, unanimously garnering league MVP honors.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1988-major-league-baseball-season] The A's surrounded him with a stellar supporting cast, led by fellow slugger Mark McGwire (with whom Canseco formed the famed "Bash Brothers" duo).
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1988-major-league-baseball-season] Aided by strong pitching from Dave Stewart and Bob Welch and the lights-out Eckersley securing 45 saves, Oakland ran away with the American League West and swept the Boston Red Sox of Boggs, Rice, and Clemens in the playoffs before falling to the Dodgers in the World Series.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1988-major-league-baseball-season] Speaking of the Dodgers, nobody expected them even to contend for the National League West title in 1988, let alone win the World Championship.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1988-major-league-baseball-season] However, the intensity and clutch hitting of Gibson (named the NL MVP at season's end) and the solid pitching of Orel Hershiser (who won a league-leading 23 games) spearheaded L.A. to a division championship by seven games over the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1988-major-league-baseball-season] In addition to his 23 victories, Hershiser led the National League with 267 innings pitched and 8 shutouts, and also set a record of 59 consecutive scoreless innings (formerly held by Dodger great Don Drysdale).
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1988-major-league-baseball-season] These accomplishments, combined with his 2.26 ERA, earned him the National League Cy Young Award.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1988-major-league-baseball-season] However, it was in the postseason that Hershiser really distinguished himself – he started Games 1 and 3 of the NLCS against the tough New York Mets, saved Game 4 in relief, and threw a complete-game shutout in Game 7.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1988-major-league-baseball-season] He hurled another complete-game shutout in Game 2 of the World Series and also helped his own cause, going 3-for-3 at the plate with a run scored and an RBI, and again went the distance in the clinching Game 5.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1988-major-league-baseball-season] Hershiser was named MVP of both the NLCS and the World Series, capping off arguably one of the greatest seasons a starting pitcher has ever had.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1989-major-league-baseball-season] The **1989 Major League Baseball season** saw the Oakland Athletics win their first World Series title since 1974.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1989-major-league-baseball-season] The American League saw the Oakland Athletics and the Toronto Blue Jays as the AL West and AL East division winners, respectively.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1989-major-league-baseball-season] Oakland dominated the entire American League with their second straight season of more than 100 wins (including postseason wins) and looked to be a future dynasty.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1989-major-league-baseball-season] The Blue Jays, powered by their offense, won their division title in the final weekend of the season.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1989-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs and San Francisco Giants stole the spotlight in the National League, but the Giants proved to be more dominant with a strong hitting presence, while the Cubs extended their streak without a World Series championship to 81 years.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1989-major-league-baseball-season] This was the last season under the television contracts with ABC and NBC.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1989-major-league-baseball-season] MLB signed new deals with CBS and ESPN to begin broadcasting games in 1990.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1990-major-league-baseball-season] The **1990 Major League Baseball season** saw the Cincinnati Reds upset the heavily favored Oakland Athletics in the World Series, for their first title since 1976.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1990-major-league-baseball-season] This was Fay Vincent's first full season as commissioner.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1990-major-league-baseball-season] McGee won the NL batting title despite being traded to Oakland in late August.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1990-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of four-year deals with CBS and ESPN.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1990-major-league-baseball-season] CBS was awarded the rights to broadcast Saturday afternoon games, the All-Star game, and the entire postseason.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1990-major-league-baseball-season] ESPN's games included *Sunday Night Baseball*, *Wednesday Night Baseball*, and doubleheaders on Tuesdays and Fridays.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The **1992** **National League Championship Series** was a semifinal series in Major League Baseball’s 1992 postseason played between the Atlanta Braves (98–64) and the Pittsburgh Pirates (96–66) from October 6 to 14.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] A rematch of the 1991 NLCS, Atlanta won the 1992 NLCS in seven games to advance to their second straight World Series.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The series ended in dramatic fashion; in the bottom of the ninth inning of Game 7, with Atlanta down 2–1 and the bases loaded, the Braves' Francisco Cabrera cracked a two-run single that scored David Justice and Sid Bream.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Bream famously slid to score the Series-winning run, beating the throw by Pirates left fielder Barry Bonds.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The Braves would go on to lose to the Toronto Blue Jays in the World Series in six games, while the Pirates did not return to the playoffs until 2013, suffering a sports-record 20 consecutive losing season drought.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] As of 2026, this is Pittsburgh’s last postseason appearance outside of the divisional round.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The Braves were attempting to return to the World Series one year after their dramatic seven-game loss to the Minnesota Twins.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Atlanta featured largely the same lineup that had won the 1991 pennant, but they still fell into a tie for last place, seven games behind the Giants, by the end of May.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] However, Atlanta went 19–6 in June and 16–9 in July and pulled away from the rest of the NL West by winning 15 of their first 18 games in August.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The Pirates were in the NLCS for the third year in a row after losing to the eventual World Series champion Cincinnati Reds in 1990 and the Braves in 1991.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] It was also the third of four straight NLCS appearances by either the Pirates or their in-state rivals, the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The 1992 NLCS would also be the first time two teams faced each other in back-to-back postseasons since 1978, when all three postseason series were rematches of 1977.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The Pirates lost slugging right fielder Bobby Bonilla to free agency after the 1991 season, replacing him with speedster Alex Cole.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Ace pitcher John Smiley was traded to the Minnesota Twins.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Future home run champion Barry Bonds won his second MVP Award and led the Pirates with 34 home runs and 103 RBI.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Pressure beyond the moment made it imperative for the Pirates to break through and win the pennant in 1992.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Financial demands had already resulted in losing Smiley and Bonilla, and the departure of pending free agents Bonds (left fielder) and Doug Drabek (starting pitcher) loomed.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] 1992 appeared to be the last chance for Pittsburgh to win with its current core of players.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The first game of the NLCS pitted Atlanta's John Smoltz against Pittsburgh ace Doug Drabek.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Smoltz was the winning pitcher in Game 7 of the previous NLCS, where the Braves shut out the Pirates, 4–0.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Drabek had won once and lost once in the 1991 NLCS.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The Braves scored all five of their runs in the first seven innings.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] In the second, Mark Lemke's single scored Sid Bream to put Atlanta on the board.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] They added two more in the fourth inning as Bream doubled to score David Justice and then scored on an error when Orlando Merced threw the ball away while attempting to field a bunt.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Jeff Blauser's home run in the fifth made it 4–0, and Terry Pendleton drove in Otis Nixon in the seventh to complete the Braves' scoring.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The Pirates' José Lind was responsible for his team's only run as he homered in the eighth inning off of Smoltz.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Lind's run, however, was the first the Pirates had scored against the Braves in 30 innings, going back to Lind's RBI single in Game 5 of the 1991 NLCS.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Smoltz went eight innings for the win, while Drabek suffered the loss and was pulled in the fifth inning.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Atlanta's Steve Avery, who defeated Pittsburgh twice in the 1991 NLCS without surrendering a run, started Game 2 in Atlanta while Danny Jackson, who was a late season acquisition from the Chicago Cubs, started for Pittsburgh.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The Braves scored early and often in Game 2.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Jackson gave up a single to Brian Hunter, then walked Ron Gant.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Damon Berryhill followed with a single to drive in Hunter, and Mark Lemke added one of his own to score Gant.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Avery then flied out to center field to score Berryhill from third, and after Otis Nixon popped out Jeff Blauser followed with a triple, scoring Berryhill and chasing Jackson from the game.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] In the fifth, Gant faced Bob Walk with the bases loaded and two out.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] On the third pitch of the at-bat Gant hit a deep fly ball to left field that cleared the fence for a grand slam home run, his first career grand slam.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] With Avery still pitching a shutout into the seventh, the Pirates struck.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] With Barry Bonds on base and one out, Lloyd McClendon doubled to score him.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Don Slaught followed with a walk and Jose Lind hit a triple after that, scoring both runners ahead of him and making it an 8–3 game.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] With Cecil Espy batting, Avery then threw a wild pitch enabling Lind to score and cut the lead in half.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] After Espy singled, Marvin Freeman came in to relieve the tiring Avery and retired Orlando Merced to get the second out.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Jay Bell followed with a single, but Mike Stanton forced Andy Van Slyke to ground out to end the inning.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The Braves put the game out of reach in the bottom of the seventh.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] With Gant on base and two outs, Stanton doubled him home.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Denny Neagle then intentionally walked Nixon and unintentionally walked Blauser, then gave up a double to Terry Pendleton to score Stanton and Nixon.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] David Justice then singled, scoring Blauser and Pendleton and ending Neagle's afternoon.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The Braves did not score again, and after Slaught scored on a passed ball in the eighth nothing further was done and the Braves took a 2–0 lead in the series with a 13–5 victory.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Avery kept his winning streak in postseason play intact, having yet to lose in five postseason starts.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Jackson took the loss after giving up the first four Atlanta runs.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] As play moved to Three Rivers Stadium in Pittsburgh, Atlanta turned to 20-game winner Tom Glavine to try to give them a 3–0 series lead.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Pittsburgh countered with rookie Tim Wakefield, a knuckleballer who had made 13 starts during the season.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The first run of the game came in the top of the fourth as Sid Bream homered to give the Braves an early 1–0 lead.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] In the bottom of the next inning, Don Slaught hit a home run of his own to tie the score.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The Pirates added a run in the sixth to take the lead as Andy Van Slyke scored on a Jeff King double.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Ron Gant hit a home run in the top of the seventh to tie the game, but the Pirates scored what proved to be the winning run in the bottom of the seventh as Van Slyke doubled to score Gary Redus.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Wakefield pitched a complete game and earned a victory.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Glavine took the loss after pitching seven innings.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Game 4 saw a rematch of the Game 1 starters, as Doug Drabek faced John Smoltz for the second time.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] As they had in Game 1, Atlanta scored early against Drabek.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] With two runners on and two out in the second, Smoltz drove in the first run by singling to center and scoring Ron Gant.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Otis Nixon followed by singling himself, scoring Mark Lemke.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Pittsburgh responded in their half by scoring twice, as a single by Alex Cole with one out scored Mike LaValliere.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] On the same play, Jose Lind scored as Jeff Blauser made a throwing error at shortstop.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Orlando Merced drove in a run in the third by doubling home Jeff King.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] In the top of the fifth, the Braves scored again as David Justice singled with two runners on, scoring Nixon.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Randy Tomlin came in to face pinch-hitter Brian Hunter, and he promptly grounded to third.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] King, however, decided to throw home to try to get Blauser at the plate and made an error allowing a second run to score.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Atlanta scored twice more the next inning as Nixon drove in Smoltz with a two out double and scored himself when Blauser singled off of Danny Cox.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Andy Van Slyke drove in Cole with a double in the seventh but the Pirates got no closer and Jeff Reardon shut them down in the ninth inning to earn his first save of the postseason.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Smoltz, in addition to scoring a run and driving in a run, stole a base and got his second win of the series.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Drabek took his second loss, having failed to get out of the fifth inning for a second time in as many starts.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The Braves now had a 3–1 series lead and needed only one more win to advance to their second consecutive World Series.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Looking to clinch the series, the Braves trotted out Steve Avery for the second time in the series.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] This time, the Pirates solved Avery after failing to do so in any of his three previous starts against them in the LCS.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Gary Redus led off the home first with a double, scoring on a single by Jay Bell.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Avery then induced a groundout off the bat of Andy Van Slyke, which turned out to be the only out he recorded.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Barry Bonds, Jeff King, and Lloyd McClendon all doubled following the first out, and three more runs scored before Avery was pulled.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] McClendon scored Bonds on a sacrifice fly in the third, Redus doubled in Don Slaught in the sixth, and Slaught drove in King in the seventh with a single to make it 7–0.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The Braves' only run came in the eighth, as Lonnie Smith led off the inning with a triple and scored on a groundout.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Smith's triple was one of only three hits Walk allowed in a complete game, the second for the Pirates in the series.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] As it took the Pirates until 2013 to reach the playoffs again, Game 5 of the NLCS was the last postseason game ever played in Three Rivers Stadium.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Game 6 saw the series return to Atlanta, with Tom Glavine taking on Tim Wakefield in a Game 3 rematch.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Once again, as in Game 5, the Pirates scored early and often.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] After retiring the Pirates in order in the first, Glavine collapsed in the second.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Barry Bonds led off with a home run, and after singles by Jeff King and Lloyd McClendon, Don Slaught drove them both in with a double.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] An error by Jeff Blauser allowed Slaught to score, and after Wakefield reached on a sacrifice bunt attempt Gary Redus hit his fourth double of the series to drive in Jose Lind.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Jay Bell then homered to score Redus and Wakefield.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Glavine was pulled after this, having faced eight batters in the second without an out.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] With the Pirates' lead at 8–1 in the fifth, Lind doubled to score Slaught and McClendon, scored himself on a single by Redus, who scored on a single by Andy Van Slyke.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] McClendon's home run in the sixth ended the Pittsburgh scoring.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] David Justice hit two home runs in the late innings but they were meaningless as the Pirates tied the series.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The stadium was largely empty by the end of the game as most fans left once the Pirates put the game out of reach—a bad omen for the Braves as seven of the previous ten teams that managed to come back from a 3–1 deficit to force a Game 7 had gone on to complete the comeback.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Wakefield again went the distance for his second win—a somewhat questionable decision by Leyland, since had he removed him earlier once he had a comfortable lead, Wakefield could have been available for relief duty in Game 7 to supplant Pittsburgh's notoriously unreliable bullpen.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Glavine's eight run, one-inning outing garnered him his second loss.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The deciding game of the NLCS featured the third matchup of the series between John Smoltz and Doug Drabek, after Games 1 and 4.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Smoltz was an MVP candidate for the series, having started and won both of his games.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Drabek had struggled in his two starts, failing to make it past the fifth inning in either matchup.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] However, the Pirates were carrying momentum from their previous two wins, having knocked out Steve Avery in the first inning and Tom Glavine in the second on their way to outscoring the Braves, 20–5, and looked to become the first team to win the NLCS after trailing, 3–1.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The game that followed was regarded as one of the greatest ever, as years later MLB Network ranked it the fourth best game of all time.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The Pirates scored first as Alex Cole led off with a walk, advanced to third on a double by Andy Van Slyke, and scored on a sacrifice fly by Orlando Merced.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The Pirates would add a run in the sixth as Jay Bell scored on a single by Van Slyke, and the lead held up as Drabek pitched his best game of the series in holding the Braves scoreless.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The closest the Braves got to breaking through was in the sixth inning, when Drabek allowed three consecutive singles to Mark Lemke, Jeff Treadway, and Otis Nixon to load the bases.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Jeff Blauser, however, lined into an unassisted double play and Terry Pendleton lined out to Barry Bonds in left to end the threat.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] An incident involving the umpires early in the game set a different tone that would come into play later on.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] In the second inning, home plate umpire John McSherry became ill and complained of nausea and dizziness.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] After being checked out by the stadium medical staff, McSherry was removed from the game as a precaution and first base umpire Randy Marsh was summoned over from his position to take over behind the plate.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The move gave both Smoltz and Drabek a different target to hit for strikes as Marsh had a consistent strike zone that was much tighter than McSherry's.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Although Drabek was able to hold the Braves in check, giving up only five hits in the first eight innings, the Pirates failed to take advantage of multiple opportunities in the late innings to add an insurance run.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Mike LaValliere led off the seventh inning with a single off of Mike Stanton, and after José Lind lined out he advanced to second on a bunt by Drabek.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Lloyd McClendon then pinch-hit for Cole and was intentionally walked.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Pete Smith then entered the game and issued a third walk to Bell, loading the bases for Van Slyke.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] However, the Braves got out of the jam when Game 5 loser Steve Avery, making a rare relief appearance, came in and induced a fly out to center field.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] After the Braves failed to score in the seventh, Avery faced the middle of the Pirates' order in the top of the eighth.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Bonds led off with a single, but was thrown out on a force play at second with Merced reaching first.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Jeff King followed with a double, but Justice threw out Merced trying to score for the second out.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] In the ninth, Braves closer Jeff Reardon retired Lind on a fly out.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] With the pitcher due next, Jim Leyland decided to keep Drabek in the game and he struck out for the second out.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] McClendon drew a walk, then advanced on a wild pitch.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Pinch runner Cecil Espy came in to replace McClendon, but he was stranded at second base as Bell grounded out.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Pittsburgh was now three outs away from advancing to their first World Series since 1979.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Terry Pendleton led off the home ninth with a double off of Drabek.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] David Justice followed by hitting a sharp grounder to José Lind, who was eventually awarded a Gold Glove at second base for the season.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Lind, however, misplayed the ball, and Pendleton advanced to third on the error.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Drabek then walked former teammate Sid Bream on four pitches, which moved the tying run into scoring position and loaded the bases.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] With the winning run now on base and Ron Gant scheduled next, Leyland made a pitching change and brought in his closer, Stan Belinda, to make his second appearance of the series and attempt to preserve the victory for Drabek, who was responsible for all three baserunners.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Gant hit a deep fly ball that was caught by Bonds, enabling Pendleton to score and put the Braves on the board.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Damon Berryhill was the next batter and worked a 3–1 count out of Belinda.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The next pitch appeared to cross the plate in the strike zone, but Marsh called it ball four; it was later speculated that at least two if not three of the pitches called balls to Berryhill would have been called strikes with McSherry behind the plate.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Berryhill’s walk once again loaded the bases and moved the winning run, represented by a relatively slow-footed baserunner in Bream, into scoring position.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] With the pitcher's spot due in two batters, Cox went to his bench for a pinch hitter and summoned Brian Hunter to bat in place of second baseman Rafael Belliard.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Belinda got him to pop up on the second pitch of the at-bat, which was caught for the second out by Lind.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Francisco Cabrera, who had only appeared in seventeen games that season for the Braves, was sent up to try and keep Atlanta's season alive.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Belinda fell behind Cabrera 2–0, then got a strike after Cabrera hit a sharp line drive foul to left.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Before the next pitch, centerfielder Van Slyke signaled to leftfielder Bonds, who was a lefthanded fielder, to move in a few steps, so as not to allow the winning run to score if Cabrera hit it to left again.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Bonds, refusing to move, responded by giving the finger to his teammate.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] On the next pitch, Cabrera again hit a liner to left.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The ball dropped in for a hit in front of Bonds, scoring Justice with the tying run.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] As Bonds went to field the ball, Atlanta third base coach Jimy Williams watched the play develop.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Bream, having had multiple knee injuries during the course of his career, was considered to be one of the slowest baserunners in the game.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] However, Williams saw that Bonds' positioning would cause him to throw the ball away from the plate, which would have forced LaValliere, the catcher to field the throw and then come back across the plate to make a tag, and thus made the decision to wave Bream around.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] As he had suspected, the throw from Bonds came in to the right, and the extra second that LaValliere needed to field the ball allowed Bream to slide in ahead of the tag with the winning run.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The victory was picked up by Jeff Reardon, who pitched the ninth inning.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The loss was charged to Drabek, who took his third defeat of the series—though two of the three the runs he was charged with were unearned, stemming from the Lind error.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Smoltz, with his two victories and solid start keeping the Braves in the game in Game 7, was named the series MVP.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Andy Van Slyke sat motionless in centerfield for several minutes after the game ended, while the Braves celebrated at home plate.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] In the celebration at home plate after Sid Bream's pennant-winning slide, Braves pitcher Kent Mercker was hurt and unable to pitch in the World Series.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Game 7 of the 1992 NLCS marked the first time (and to date, still the only time) in MLB history that a team which was one out away from losing in a winner-take-all game of a playoff series instead won on the last pitch.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] To date, Francisco Cabrera is the only player in MLB history to win a postseason series with a hit during an at bat in which he could have lost the series with an out.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] All other series walk-off hits occurred either with the score already tied (as with Bill Mazeroski's 1960 World Series winning home run) or in a game that was not winner-take-all, as with Joe Carter's home run to win the 1993 World Series, which occurred in Game 6.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The March 1993 issue of *Baseball Digest* pronounced it the greatest baseball comeback ever, as did John Smoltz immediately after the game.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] A 2006 study by the *Pittsburgh Post-Gazette* pronounced Cabrera's game-winning single the eighth-"clutchest" hit in MLB history.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] ESPN called the Pirates' defeat the eighth most painful in baseball history.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Don Ohlmeyer, the former head of NBC Sports and President of NBC West Coast, supposedly called the event "one of the most exciting baseball moments he had ever seen".
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Game 7 was the last postseason game for the Pirates until 2013, when the team faced and defeated the Cincinnati Reds in the National League Wild Card Game.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The Pirates also went 20 years without a winning season after 1992.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Game 7 was the last Pirates game for Bonds and Drabek who left via free agency, signing with the Giants and Astros, respectively.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Until 2008, the Braves were the last team in Major League Baseball to win a seventh game after blowing a 3–1 series lead, and only the fourth of 11 total to do it up to that point.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] That year, the Tampa Bay Rays won Game 7 of the ALCS after blowing a 3–1 lead to the Boston Red Sox.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The Braves lost the 1992 World Series to the Toronto Blue Jays in six games.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] 1992 was the second of five National League pennants for the Braves from 1991 to 1999.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] After making their second consecutive NLCS in 1992, the Braves made seven of the next nine that followed.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] In 1993, the Braves again came back from a second half deficit to win their division, but were upset by the Philadelphia Phillies in the NLCS.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Atlanta won their first World Series under Bobby Cox in 1995.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] They lost the 1996 and 1999 World Series to the New York Yankees.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] In 1997, the Braves fell to Jim Leyland's Marlins in the NLCS and in 1998, they were defeated by the San Diego Padres.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] After being defeated in the NLDS in 2000, the Braves made it back to the NLCS in 2001 only be defeated by the eventual World Series champion Arizona Diamondbacks.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Their most recent NLCS appearance came in 2021, where they defeated the defending World Series champion Los Angeles Dodgers in six games en route to winning the 2021 World Series over the Houston Astros in six games to win their fourth World Series championship.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Francisco Cabrera went 0–1 in the 1992 Series.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] He played only one more season in the big leagues, accruing 91 plate appearances for the 1993 Braves.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Louis Cardinals' Dominican League affiliate.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Bobby Cox eventually retired as Braves manager following the 2010 season, and was elected to the Hall of Fame in 2014.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] He was joined by his ace from this series, Tom Glavine, who was elected as a player that same year and won 305 games in his career.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] "The Slide" also proved to be the end of the Pirates' stretches of playoff runs after losing three straight NLCS.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The Pirates never recovered from their loss to the Braves, going 75–87 in 1993.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The Pirates would not have another winning season until 2013; their streak of 20 consecutive losing seasons through 2012 remains an all-time record for major North American professional sports.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Barry Bonds and Doug Drabek played their last games for the team, as both departed in free agency that offseason.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Bonds went to the San Francisco Giants, where he played for the remainder of his career and eventually set baseball's all-time single season and career home run record with 73 and 762 respectively.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Bonds became eligible for the Hall of Fame in 2013, but has yet to be elected due in part to concerns about his use of performance-enhancing drugs.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] After years of bad blood with the organization, Bonds was inducted into the Pirates Hall of Fame in 2024.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Drabek signed with the Houston Astros and stayed there for four seasons, but did not maintain the consistency that he had in Pittsburgh and eventually retired in 1998.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Manager Jim Leyland stayed with the Pirates through the 1996 season, with his team losing 80 or more games three of those four years.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] He moved on to the Florida Marlins, where his team beat Cox's Braves in the NLCS and went on to win the World Series in 1997.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] Leyland moved on to manage the Detroit Tigers to two World Series losses in 2006 and 2012 (including 3 straight ALCS appearances from 2011–13) before retiring following the 2013 season.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] As of 2026, this is Pittsburgh’s last postseason appearance outside of the divisional round, and this is their most recent postseason appearance as a division champion, as the Pirates hold the longest division title drought in the majors.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The only team of the four major North American leagues with a longer division title drought are the NFL’s Cleveland Browns, who last won their division in 1989, three years before Pittsburgh’s last division title.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1992-national-league-championship-series] The 1990-1992 Pirates are also the last team to lose three consecutive League Championship Series.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] The **1994 Major League Baseball season** began on April 3, but ended prematurely on August 11, 1994, with the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] The season started despite the expiration of MLB's previous collective bargaining agreement at the end of 1993.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] It was the first season played under the current three-division format in each league.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] It was also the first with an Opening Night game involving two National League teams, which did not become permanent until 1996.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] As a result of a players' strike, the MLB season ended prematurely on August 11, 1994.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] No postseason (including the World Series) was played.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Over 260 players were scheduled to exceed $1 million in compensation in 1994.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] The Minor League Baseball season was played in its entirety.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] MLB Baseball would not attempt another salary cap until 2026.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of The Baseball Network, the joint venture between MLB, ABC, and NBC.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, ESPN renewed its contract for *Sunday Night Baseball* and *Wednesday Night Baseball*.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Under The Baseball Network's original plan, the All-Star Game would alternate between NBC in even-numbered years and ABC in odd-numbered years.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] After the All-Star Game was complete, ABC took over coverage with what was to be their weekly slate of games under the *Baseball Night in America* banner.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] ABC was scheduled to televise six regular season games on Saturdays or Mondays in prime time.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] NBC would then pick up where ABC left off by televising six more regular season Friday night games.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Every *Baseball Night in America* game was scheduled to begin at 8 p.m.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Pacific Time if the game occurred on the West Coast).
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] A single starting time gave the networks the opportunity to broadcast one game and then, simultaneously, cut to another game when there was a break in action.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] The networks had exclusive rights for the twelve regular season dates, in that no regional or national cable service (such as ESPN or superstations like Chicago's WGN-TV or Atlanta's WTBS) or over-the-air broadcaster was allowed to telecast a Major League Baseball game on those dates.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] *Baseball Night in America* (which premiered on July 16, 1994) usually aired up to fourteen games based on the viewers' region (affiliates chose games of local interest to carry) as opposed to a traditional coast-to-coast format.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Normally, announcers who represented each of the teams playing in the respective games were paired with each other.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] More specifically, on regional Saturday night broadcasts and all non-"national" broadcasts, TBN let the two lead announcers from the opposing teams call the games involving their teams together.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] Postseason coverage would have also alternated between the two networks.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] In even-numbered years, NBC would have the rights to the All-Star Game and both League Championship Series while ABC would have the World Series and newly created Division Series.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/1994-major-league-baseball-season] When the player's strike began on August 12, ABC had only aired games on four of its six scheduled dates, while NBC's slate was supposed to begin on August 26.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] After his playing career McClendon served as the manager of the Pittsburgh Pirates from 2001 to 2005 and the Seattle Mariners from 2014 to 2015.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] He most recently served as the interim manager for the Detroit Tigers in 2020.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] In 1971, McClendon played in the Little League World Series for his hometown Gary, Indiana, team, and earned the nickname "Legendary Lloyd" by homering in five consecutive at bats.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] In fact, they were his only official at-bats; in all his other plate appearances, the opposing coaches had him intentionally walked.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] McClendon's 1971 team was the first all-African American team to reach the final stage of the LLWS.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] He attended Roosevelt High School in Gary and graduated in 1977.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] McClendon played collegiate baseball at Valparaiso University, not far from Gary.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] While at Valparaiso, he compiled a career batting average of .330, and produced 18 home runs and 73 runs batted in.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] Twice he received all-conference honors (1979 and 1980).
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] McClendon was drafted by the New York Mets in the 8th round of the 1980 Major League Baseball draft as a catcher.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] He began his professional baseball career with the Kingsport Mets of the Appalachian League.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] While playing at the A ball level for the Lynchburg Mets, McClendon was roomed with teammate Darryl Strawberry by their manager, Gary Dusan, as Strawberry was struggling with adversity and McClendon a positive influence.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] 43 years later, shortly before Strawberry had his uniform number 18 retired by the New York Mets, Strawberry recalled in an interview how helpful both Dusan and McClendon had been helping him survive a particularly challenging season and enabling him to go on to a successful major league career.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] After the 1982 season, he was traded along with two other players to the Cincinnati Reds in a deal to bring Mets legend Tom Seaver back to New York.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] 1983 was the first season in which McClendon began to get significant time at positions other than catcher, playing both third and first base while with the Waterbury Reds.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] He continued to be used as a utility player over the next several seasons, before finally breaking into the majors with the Reds in 1987.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] McClendon made his major league debut on Opening Day in 1987 as a pinch hitter, He spent most of the season with the Reds, aside from a brief return to the minors with the Nashville Sounds in August.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] He played in 45 games, mostly as a pinch hitter, but also appeared at five different positions in the field (catcher, first base, third base, and left and right field).
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] 1988 saw McClendon playing a similar role, although his playing time increased.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] He again played five positions on defense while batting .219 in 72 games overall.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] After the season, he was traded to the Chicago Cubs for outfielder Rolando Roomes.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] McClendon saw the most playing time of his major league career with the Cubs in 1989.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] Playing mostly left field and first base, he batted .286 with career highs in home runs with 12 and runs batted in with 40.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] He also scored a career-best 47 runs and even stole 6 bases.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] McClendon struggled at the plate in 1990, however, playing in 49 games for the Cubs and batting an anemic .159.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] Late in the season, he was traded to the Pirates for a player to be named later.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] McClendon played in 4 games for the Pirates at the end of 1990, going 1-for-3 at the plate.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] He played for the Pirates through the end of the 1994 season, spending most of his time in the outfield.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] In the 1992 postseason, he batted .727 while playing in five games of the 1992 National League Championship Series, collecting eight hits in eleven at-bats.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] It is the highest batting average posted in one postseason.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] He was hitting .239 in 1994 when the season was interrupted - and ultimately ended - by a players' strike.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] After the season he became a free agent.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] McClendon signed a minor league contract with the Cleveland Indians in 1995.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] After failing to make the team out of spring training, he was assigned to the Buffalo Bisons.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] He played 37 games, including his first games at third base since 1990.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] However, he never received a promotion to the majors, and retired after the season.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] After retiring from playing, McClendon served as a hitting coach for the Pirates until he was appointed manager after the 2000 season.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] At the time of his hiring, he became the first African American manager or head coach of any of Pittsburgh's three major sports teams, preceding the Steelers hiring of Mike Tomlin by six years.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] McClendon held the Pirates managerial position until he was fired September 6, 2005.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] In his five seasons as manager of the Pirates, McClendon compiled a 336–446 record.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] When Jim Leyland was hired as manager of the Detroit Tigers, he brought former player McClendon on board as bullpen coach.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] For the 2007 season, he was promoted to hitting coach, replacing former Pirates teammate Don Slaught.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] On May 28, 2010, he changed his jersey number from 12 to 19 due to Gerald Laird changing his jersey number from 8 to 12.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] The Tigers did not have an official bench coach until Gene Lamont was named to that position for the 2013 season, but McClendon served a part of that role as acting manager in the absence of Jim Leyland.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] A Detroit player won the American League batting title in four of McClendon's seven seasons as the team's hitting coach.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] On November 5, 2013, the *Puget Sound Business Journal* reported that McClendon would be the new Seattle Mariners manager.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] On November 7, general manager Jack Zduriencik officially announced McClendon as the team's manager.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] In McClendon's first season as the manager of the Mariners, the team finished with an 87–75 record.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] The team's record represented an improvement from 71–91 in 2013.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] However, in 2015, the Mariners struggled and finished 76–86; McClendon was fired on October 9, 2015.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] He finished with a record of 163 wins and 161 losses.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] On November 23, 2015, McClendon was hired as the manager of the Triple-A affiliate of the Detroit Tigers, the Toledo Mud Hens.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] In the 2016 season, the Mud Hens struggled, finishing 68–76.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] Following that season, McClendon was named the Tigers' new hitting coach.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] On October 21, 2016, McClendon was named the Tigers' hitting coach, a position he previously held with the team from 2007 to 2013.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] On September 30, 2019, McClendon succeeded Steve Liddle as the Tigers' bench coach.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] On September 19, 2020, McClendon was named interim manager of the Tigers following the retirement of Ron Gardenhire.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] After the 2020 season, the Tigers named A.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] Hinch as the team's new manager, and McClendon was not retained on the coaching staff.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] On January 27, 2022, McClendon was hired to manage the Triple-A affiliate of the Detroit Tigers, the Toledo Mud Hens for a second time, following the promotion of Mud Hens manager Gary Jones to first base coach for the major league team.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] On December 18, 2025, McClendon was hired to serve as the manager for the Piratas de Campeche of the Mexican League.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] McClendon has a history of challenging close calls on the diamond, and stated his belief that the Pirates didn't always get fair calls from the umpires.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] As he put it during the 2002 season, "I'm sure it's nothing intentional on their part.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] I certainly would never question their integrity.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] But it's human nature to relax a little and take something for granted.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] We've lost for so long that I think it's easy for umpires to lose respect for us and take us for granted.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] If I get thrown out of 100 games, then I get thrown out of 100 games.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] I'm going to keep demanding a playing field that's equal for my players.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] On June 26, 2001, in a game against the Milwaukee Brewers, McClendon saw two questionable calls made against his Pirates by the first base umpire, Rick Reed.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] After Jason Kendall was called out at first base, McClendon went onto the field to argue the call.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] After being ejected from the game, McClendon removed first base and walked off the field with it, later throwing it into the dugout, where a batboy placed a Pirates cap on top of it.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] Rather than risk McClendon's wrath by retrieving the base, the field crew replaced the base with a new one.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] The Pirates rallied to win the game in the 12th inning, 7–6.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] The next day, the players mounted the base in their clubhouse.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] 4 place on ESPN.com Page 2's "Coaches Gone Wild" list, which jokingly called it an incident of "stealing" first.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] In the 2005 season, McClendon exhibited signs of a desire to end this tendency.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] During a series against the Washington Nationals at the end of June, when replays of the first base theft were being shown on the scoreboard, he said, "I don't like that being shown, I don't want people to identify (that) with me.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] However, on June 2, 2015, McClendon once again made national news after challenging the entire umpire crew after a couple of questionable check-swing calls by Brett Gardner and Alex Rodriguez during the Mariners game against the New York Yankees.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] Mariners catcher Mike Zunino expressed displeasure with first base umpire Will Little's safe call on a check swing, leading to Zunino's ejection.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] McClendon initially argued with home plate umpire Mike DiMuro before throwing his hat and proceeding to argue with Little, eventually kicking his hat and running around the diamond to argue with each member of the umpiring crew.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] Following their 2010 season, the Seattle Mariners interviewed McClendon, as well as several others, for their managerial position, with Seattle eventually deciding to hire Eric Wedge.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] On October 30, 2012, McClendon was interviewed by the Miami Marlins as a candidate to succeed Ozzie Guillén, who was fired after a single season.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] However, the Marlins hired Mike Redmond instead.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] On October 24, 2013, McClendon interviewed for the Tigers' managerial job, but that job went to Brad Ausmus.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] On November 3, 2013, McClendon was in Seattle for a second interview for the managerial job for the Mariners.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] He ultimately was hired by the Mariners as their new manager beginning in the 2014 season.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] McClendon is one of twelve or thirteen children.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] McClendon met Ingrid Scott while the two were students at Valparaiso University; They went on to marry in 1981.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] The couple has two children, daughter Schenell (born c.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] Schenell graduated Valparaiso, followed by law school, then married in 2014.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] Bo also attended Valparaiso, and was a 39th round draft choice the Detroit Tigers in 2010.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] He played in the minor leagues for two years.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] Granddaughter Bryn was born to Schenell and her husband in 2019.
[src:lloyd-mcclendon/lloyd-mcclendon] McClendon and his wife continue to live in Indiana.
